<li id="cite_note-30"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-30">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.monitor.bg/article?id=221390">The Yanks oppose more US troops in Afghanistan</a> <i>(in Bulgarian)</i> Monitor.bg, 13 Nov 2009. Retrieved 16 Sept 2012.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-31"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-31">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">This is especially true in the case of brand names –</span>
<dl>
<dd>
<dl>
<dd><span class="reference-text">Wikileaks, YouTube, Skype – as opposed to Уикилийкс, Ю-Тюб, Скайп</span></dd>
</dl>
</dd>
<dd><span class="reference-text">However, this is not always the case –</span>
<dl>
<dd><span class="reference-text">Фейсбук VS Гугъл <sup>(<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://paper.standartnews.com/bg/article.php?article=352223">Standart News</a>)</sup> (literal transliteration: <i>Feysbuk vs Gugal</i>)</span></dd>
</dl>
</dd>
<dd><span class="reference-text">Note the inconsistency here – despite the insistence on Cyrillic, the "vs" has been retained in Roman script.</span></dd>
</dl>
